    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-04-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-04-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="1390"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1390">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.52/236.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Consul <persName type="from">Letcher</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Chihuahua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-04-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 15, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department’s April 11. Carranza replies through Secretary Foreign Affairs that
                    his attitude in case of Spaniards is identical with that assumed in Benton
                        case,<note n="117" xml:id="d1390fn117">Protection of British interests, <ref
                            target="#pg_856">pp. 856</ref>–<ref target="#pg_857">857</ref>. See
                        also, under protection of German interests, Mr. Letcher’s April 15, 1
                        p.m.</note> that is to say that interested governments must address
                    themselves to Carranza through the Department of State and then only when there
                    is no accredited representative of such country on the ground. Fabela explains
                    verbally that this attitude should not be construed to imply any lack of
                    gratitude on part of Carranza for favors shown by our Government but that it is
                    assumed to force other foreign countries to deal directly with Carranza on
                    matters affecting their respective nationals, such dealings <pb facs="0923"
                        n="807" xml:id="pg_807"/> constituting quasi recognition of
                    Constitutionalist Government. He further points out that Great Britain has
                    already accepted Carranza’s requirements.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Letcher</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
